<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the CBI (RaD0012)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the CBI (RaD0012)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Response of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CBI</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The CBI is the UK’s leading business organisation, speaking for some 240,000 businesses that together employ around a third of the private sector workforce.  With offices across the UK as well as representation in Brussels, Washington, Beijing and Delhi th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e CBI communicates the British business voice globally. CBI members include the 17 UK-based companies that invest most in R&amp;D.  Many other CBI members which are not headquartered in the UK also invest heavily in R&amp;D in this country.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We welcome this opportu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nity to respond to the Select Committee’s invitation to offer suggestions for future inquiries on UK R&amp;D funding.  The NAO study has brought together a useful array of facts and figures on an important subject and provides a basis for pursuing a number of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lines of investigation, including the causes and consequences of the changing balance of R&amp;D funding sources and the reasons for the long-term decline and subsequent stagnation of UK national R&amp;D intensity over a period when R&amp;D intensity has been rising i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n many other countries.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We wish specifically to suggest that the Committee should give high priority to an inquiry into </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">improving the UK environment for R&amp;D by mid-sized businesses</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (MSBs), by which we mean typically businesses with a turnover of about £10m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-£500m, but particularly those in the lower part of this range, from £10-£100m.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Increasing the competitiveness of mid-sized businesses would significantly benefit the economy</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">As the NAO study has demonstrated, business R&amp;D expenditure in the UK is highly c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">oncentrated in a small number of large firms, particularly in the pharmaceuticals sector.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> While it is welcome that the UK is an attractive location for these companies to conduct R&amp;D on a substantial scale, there would be benefits to be had from a broader</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> distribution of investment in R&amp;D.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> In particular, R&amp;D which underpins innovation adds to the competitive advantage of businesses, increasing their potential for growth including expansion into overseas markets.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> If a higher proportion of MSBs were to inc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rease their levels of innovativeness, there would be significant benefits for the wider economy.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> One of the constraints on growing R&amp;D in MSBs may be that the ecosystem for these businesses in the UK does not support them as it could, particularly in rela</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tion to innovation.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> If the Committee could identify ways in which that ecosystem can be made more supportive it would be doing a valuable service.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The CBI’s 2011 report, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Future Champions,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> pointed out that MSBs have the potential to be a powerful engine of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> growth for the UK economy but are often overlooked or neglected by policymakers and others.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Firms with a turnover of between £10m and £100m represent just 1% of firms, but account for 22% of economic revenue and 16% of total employment.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The fastest-grow</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ing among them account for a large proportion of new private sector jobs.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> But overall their productivity is lower than that of larger firms, and the gap has been widening.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Between 2002 and 2009 the growth in productivity amongst the UK’s MSBs was 5%, clo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">se to the rate of growth for small firms at 4.8%, but much slower than large firms that grew their productivity by 5.6%, despite the fact that a larger proportion of them are in sectors with high productivity growth.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Closing or reversing this gap would pa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">y substantial dividends.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">MSBs account for a low share of business R&amp;D and engage less with external partners</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The 2008 Community Innovation Survey reveals that only 62.5% of ‘medium-sized’ businesses in the UK describe themselves as innovating, compared wit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">h 84% in Germany and 67% in France, and in absolute terms they spend less on R&amp;D than their counterparts in other leading European economies.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The NAO’s study for the Committee found that, although small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) between them acc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ount for 23% of all business R&amp;D funding in the UK, if SMEs which are part of a larger enterprise group are excluded the proportion is only 4%. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Most of the larger SMEs fall within our definition of MSB, and the NAO’s figure – which has been broadly stable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> since 2000 – implies that the UK’s independent MSBs account for a strikingly low share of business R&amp;D.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A CBI survey of MSBs found that 37% of companies considered ‘collaboration with others to innovate’ to be an important driver of growth.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> But relativel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">y few MSBs are collaborating with wider innovation partners such as universities, government labs and private research organisations.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> They are also much less likely to seek partners across Europe compared with larger companies.  In general MSBs seem less </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">apt to take part in the open innovation approach which is widely adopted by larger companies and many smaller ones.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Improving the ecosystem for MSBs could increase innovation and competitiveness</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">One obstacle to engagement with universities and other forms </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of partnering arises from the more limited capacity MSBs tend to have, both administratively to develop and manage engagement and technically to participate in knowledge exchange.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> It also appears that government and other support schemes have lower visibi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lity for MSBs than they do for larger companies – partly because they do not have the resources to scan for them.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> But it is also likely that the innovation ecosystem for these businesses is not well adapted to their needs.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> For example, MSBs can be expect</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ed to have more need than larger companies of support in commercialising technologies at an intermediate level of readiness.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Committee is well placed to investigate constraints on innovation activities by MSBs and to identify possible remedies.  Improv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ements in the ecosystem could raise levels of R&amp;D investment underpinning innovation and increase productivity and competitiveness.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Questions the Committee may wish to consider include:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Are the new Catapult centres being designed to enable them to meet the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> requirements of MSBs?  Could more be learned from the funding model of Germany’s Fraunhofer institutes?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Does the infrastructure for UK business engagement with European R&amp;D funding, particularly through the current Framework Programme and in future throug</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">h Horizon 2020, provide adequate support for MSB involvement?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">MSBs, particularly manufacturers, seem </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">less likely than either large or smaller businesses to make use of the R&amp;D tax credit, despite the fact that even fairly  large MSBs may benefit from a hig</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hly favourable offer: w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hat are the obstacles to ensuring the R&amp;D tax credit provides an effective incentive to MSBs?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Has the Technology Strategy Board succeeded in ensuring innovative MSBs are aware of what is has to offer them, and could that offer be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">improved?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Do the Research Councils have appropriate business engagement strategies in place for MSBs?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Is there scope to do more to promote MSB engagement with universities, and ensuring a wider awareness of the potential value of the ‘Lambert toolkit’ for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">IP negotiations? Are there useful lessons for the UK as a whole to be learned from the Interface programme which helps to connect businesses with universities in Scotland?</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Should a more strategic approach be taken to promoting and facilitating MSB engagement with the existing independent research and technology organisations such as MIRA, TWI and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Campden BRI?  Might there be scope for a widened ‘innovation voucher’ scheme to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> stimulate MSB engagement with a range of knowledge providers?</span></li></ul><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We would be happy to elaborate on these suggestions or to assist the Committee in any other way that might be of use.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>